Austria’s right-wing populists triumph, they have 29 percent in total
Preliminary results show that the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current president Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly significant losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at the national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 percent of the votes, the country's leading political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the votes.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent loses nearly nine percent of the vote, finished even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major parties of the post-war period; especially for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Still at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
Now, the voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations were made about the possible resignation of the party leader and current Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
The observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the leadership of the party.
Such an evolution would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election that remains most likely, namely the renewal of the large coalition SPÖ and ÖVP.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties – the Free Party (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the votes – the Socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the People’s Party agreed with the populists (at the time the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ split from the common.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna on the national political scene, apparently bets on this evolution.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell, among the Austrian political parties, from third to fifth position.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four per cent limit and did not reach parliament.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India likely to cool
If the problem of accused Czech researchers in India accused of illegal cockroach harvesting could not be resolved, Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg said, there would be some cooling of Czech-Indian relations.
The minister said this today in New York, after meeting his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not solved, then yes, some cooling would occur," he said after the meeting, which followed a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, on leaving the talks, that the executive could hardly intervene in judicial cases.
He mentioned, however, that in the case of Petr Ivácha, who was discharged from the charge and punished with a fine, the central government could negotiate with the local government, that of Darjeling, the case being placed under the jurisdiction of the latter.
"Their problem could be solved," the minister said.
According to Mukherjee, the best solution for the three-year prison sentence would be to appeal to a higher court.
He could then seek bail and await trial on release, he said.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner also spoke in the same direction during the talks.
"He advises appealing to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned," says the head of Czech diplomacy.
The only way in which the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide the convicts with "competent legal support", the Indian minister said.
He also said that such assistance had already been provided by India.
“We want above all to keep the best relations with India, which have a tradition that continues over many years.
The Indians recognize it as well,” Schwarzenberg said.
At the same time, as he told TK, he pointed out to his partner that the Czech Republic attached great importance to the problem of Czech entomologies.
“We regard the incarceration and accusation of these Czech researchers as a great contempt,” he said.
The minister evaded the question of whether he got a promise from India to take care of the case.
“I’ve already received quite a few promises,” he said.
A Czech arbiter of the fight for the seabed
It approaches an electronic wall map, on which is represented Australia and adjacent marine areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
“The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is as large as the continent itself," said Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of thirty members of the UN division for ocean affairs and the law of the sea.
Its head, the director of the division, the Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
Work ardor and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a little known world, rich in natural resources.
It includes oil, minerals and other mineral resources, as well as currently unknown living organisms, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A wider ground than the dry land
The coastal states have begun to aspire vehemently to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are using their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
It is mainly the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter can, according to the convention, claim exclusively to all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea, is considered a continental shelf.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone,” explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf, must be supported by extensive scientific-technical documentation, based on many expensive prospections and expertise.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
“One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
At the moment, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," Mikulka adds.
The success of Australia, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently experienced a global repercussion.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission awarded it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which is six times the extent of the country.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The future benefits of seabed exploitation will be invaluable, as they plan to do.
Progressively, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention".
Here, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There is no longer a state with an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, let's not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," said Director Mikulka, adding that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime is anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed today also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other former Eastern bloc states in the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, under the Convention, as well as investors from a few other states, it obtained the status of a so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, Hawaii and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The background is turbulent, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese,” says Ind Pakshi Rajan, another jurist.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such a concretization.
It is reminiscent of a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
