Organizers report an increasing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
When it comes to bookings for the coming months, according to a study, the turnover has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even by more than 30 percent.
Despite weak cyclical prospects, Germans’ thirst for travel remains insatiable, according to this study.
When it comes to bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded revenues of more than 31 percent compared to the same period the previous year, as reported Monday in Berlin by the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV).
According to the survey by the GfK Market Research Institute, growing numbers of bookings already dominate the autumn months.
Thus, the sales figure would have risen to about 11 percent more compared to 2007, DRV said.
The sources of these results are figures from the GfK, which analyzes monthly booking data from 1,200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the global market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
Due to the low price of the dollar, travel to the US would be particularly in demand, the DRV said.
There, the increase in bookings would amount to about one-third.
Apart from that, Spain, Turkey and Greece as well as our country would be particularly sought after destinations by the Germans.
Specially organized trips are in high demand, said DRV President Klaus Laepple.
Given the rising prices of energy and food, the costs would here be "more easily computable for the customer than for an individually organized trip".
Consumers can save money, among other things, with early booking discounts or All Inclusive offerings, Laepple said.
The summer months were also very successful so that an increase in sales figures will be recorded again compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who undertook a trip decreased compared to the previous year.
