Morgan Stanley opens its capital at MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry in its turn of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan’s first bank, which will pay $9 billion to take 21% of its capital, a new one welcomed by a sharp drop in its stock price.
A week after unveiling an interim deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of the Morgan Stanley common stock at a unit price of $25.25, or a total amount of $3 billion.
The chosen price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as of August 31.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in convertible securities with a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley lost 6.79% to $23.07 around 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to bank holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s chief executive.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but puts it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: Last Monday, Morgan simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, explained to Tokyo, “we thought that the stake would be entirely made up of ordinary shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into common shares in a year if they trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or about $47, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
However, a spokeswoman for the group declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" eased its balance sheet since late August.
The past few weeks have been challenging for the group, which has seen its stock market price melt by half as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt soared.
This cost fell on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Reshaping the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like its counterparts and friends, it was the third to vote on a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" scored 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted outside polling stations and a count from a non-governmental organization announced a broad “yes” victory, placing it between 63 and 70 percent.
Rafael Correa claimed on Sunday night the victory of his draft Constitution.
“The Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place calmly according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, focused on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution consecrates state power over the economy, reserving it the “development planning” of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the draft also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad.
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who were captured 10 days ago.
They are in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive for 10 days in the desert were safely returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently fit, the hostages arrived at around 15:30 a.m. aboard a special aircraft at al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, on helicopters to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in “good health,” and “no ransom has been paid” to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the outskirts of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one hideout to the other by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the safari agency Aegyptus.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others were fleeing," said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our secret service, special forces men," he said, without further details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board which were the kidnappers, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed they were linked to a rebel group from Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement had immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and occupies the current electoral campaign.
Good.
But one area of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery that are given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that starve?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that he neglects his monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros on the restoration of the Château de Chinon alone in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and this in concert.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with searching history, preserving with three under private archive clusters and preserving archaeological remains.
They are often the watchdogs of our heritage, protesting with the energy of despair when promoters and decision makers throw their bulldozers at our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When is a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux Governments Nationalize Part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states help the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European bank in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, to the tune of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, also calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s head of competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has escalated in more than a year is for Fortis, and from a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (to the tune of 49%) of the bank’s capital located in each of the countries.
The bank will, without a doubt, sell part of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the mainly insurance activities, which it acquired last year from the Dutch organisation ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, shares have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's executives, is not realistic.
The company's management accuses the uncertainty of overseas, in connection with the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout, of being at the root of the fall in Fortis stocks.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Earlier, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they will not lose their money.
No panics were felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agencies were stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become out of control.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information about the prescription of medicines, in all cases, with the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like handing over your chicken coop to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told The Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage, on the health of the client who presents, and if they believe the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after they had seen the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it can easily be provided to pharmacies, data on the person's purchases of drugs in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease the person suffers from and what his health is.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer apart from paperwork. However, tiny problems can still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or against hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of the data, and they must seek the authorization of the patient before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their shortcomings in the past.
In recent years, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them with data on drug consumption, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of usage is becoming more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to expand the circle of authorities’ control over companies specializing in providing data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
So, in the end, the chickens depend on the kindness of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The EU and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other problems, largely global.
Today, a France-India summit will also be held, where the main issue will be atomic energy cooperation.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a wider say in international affairs, but member countries have yet to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not spend too much time on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Prime Minister of India, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be too ambitious a goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civilian flights, which will also allow air trade to take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and, on the other, New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, along with all forms of terrorism, and there has been talk of the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this issue.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle was also called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains true to the energy and climate agenda, including that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 percent until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as with the fact that a global market should be reached at the climate conference scheduled for next year, and greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is now visiting the French capital, where during a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency, the agreement would last 15 years.
