Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at 3,000 meters above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammown Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
“The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared,” Anderson said.
The sheriff said no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) said a few hours after the wreck was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft as the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a pull.
Fossett's search was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
On his sixth attempt in 2002, he became the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a copilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect.
An extraordinary 4x4 of an original and well-defined design, with marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
This is, in short, Glk, the last born of the off road "compact" of the house of the star, with which Mercedes-Benz tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
Thanks to its extraordinary, unexpected and unconventional content, communication will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in the Mercedes-Benz showrooms, from 17 October.
Thus the hype that will accompany the start of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, which will dominate the heart of Milanese shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication involves the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimension and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, we will have the impression that when looking at the image, the car comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of the innovative Elimina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recompose into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertising, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future buyers? We will see.
